    <h1>How Do I Leave an Abusive Relationship?</h1>
    <p>Leaving is often the most dangerous time. You don't have to plan it alone.</p>
  </div>
</div>

<section>
  <div class="wrap">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout">
        <p><strong>A note on safety:</strong> If you're worried someone monitors your phone, computer, or browser history, use the <strong>Quick Escape</strong> button (or press Esc) to leave this site instantly. When possible, browse from a device your partner doesn't have access to, such as a library or a trusted friend's computer, and clear your history afterward.</p>
      </div>

      <h2>Before you go</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Avoid telling your abuser you're planning to leave — the period right before and after leaving is often the most dangerous.</li>
        <li>Talk to an advocate. Call our 24-hour crisis line to build a safety plan specific to your situation, even if you're not ready to leave yet.</li>
        <li>Identify a safe place to go — a shelter, a trusted friend or family member, or another safe location your abuser doesn't know.</li>
        <li>If you can, set aside a small amount of money over time, including change, somewhere your abuser won't find it.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Documents to gather</h2>
      <p>If it's safe to do so, gather and securely hide copies of:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Birth certificates and Social Security cards for you and your children</li>
        <li>Passports, driver's license, or other ID</li>
        <li>Insurance paperwork and financial documents</li>
        <li>Any protective orders, if you already have one</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Packing an emergency bag</h2>
      <p>Consider keeping a bag ready — with a trusted friend or family member, or another safe location — with:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Some money, including change</li>
        <li>A change of clothes for each family member</li>
        <li>A small supply of any prescription medication</li>
        <li>Copies of important documents</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>After you leave</h2>
      <p>Our advocates can help with emergency shelter, protective orders, court accompaniment, and connecting you with other community resources. You don't need to have this figured out on your own — that's what we're here for.</p>
